# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gas-mask
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The **NIOSH air filtration rating** is the U.S.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH)'s classification of filtering respirators.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The ratings describe the ability of the device to protect the wearer from solid and liquid particulates in the air.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The certification and approval process for respiratory protective devices is governed by Part 84 of Title 42 of the Code of Federal Regulations (42 CFR 84).
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Respiratory protective devices so classified include air-purifying respirators (APR) such as filtering facepiece respirators and chemical protective cartridges that have incorporated particulate filter elements.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The NIOSH-provided classifications only cover the filtration of particles or aerosols, not the air-purifying respirator's ability to remove chemical gasses and vapors from air, which is regulated under 42 CFR 84 Subpart L.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] For chemical cartridge classifications, NIOSH, under 42 CFR 84, partially defers to American National Standard ANSI K13.1-1973.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] All classifications assume that the respirator is properly fitted.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] During the COVID-19 pandemic, the mask and respirator market rapidly grew, along with counterfeit respirators.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] NIOSH, on behalf of the Department of Health and Human Services, filed a trademark application on June 17, 2020, for various 42 CFR 84 trademarks, including the N95, allowing NIOSH to enforce rules on counterfeit masks outside of rules defined in 42 CFR 84.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] It is illegal in the United States to use filtration terms coined under 42 CFR 84, or mark masks with the word "NIOSH" without the approval of NIOSH.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Information about approved respirators can be found in the NIOSH certified equipment list (CEL).
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Prior to the 1970s, respirator standards were under the purview of the US Bureau of Mines (USBM).
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] An example of an early respirator standard, Type A, established in 1926, was intended to protect against mechanically generated dusts produced in mines.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] These standards were intended to obviate miner deaths, noted to have reached 3,243 by 1907.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Prior to the Hawks Nest Tunnel disaster, these standards were merely advisory, as the USBM had no enforcement power at the time.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] After the disaster, an explicit approval program was established in 1934, along with the introduction of combination Type A/B/C respirator ratings, corresponding to Dusts/Fumes/Mists respectively, with Type D blocking all three, under 30 CFR 14 Schedule 21.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Prior to the approval of 42 CFR 84, MSHA and NIOSH approved respirators under 30 CFR 11.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Non-powered respirator filters were classified based on their design against a contaminant, including substances like Dusts, Fumes, Mists, radionuclides, and asbestos.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Dust/Mist was usually tested with silica, and Fume was usually tested with lead fume.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The most popular respirator filters were often referred to as DM (Dust/Mist) or DFM (Dust/Fume/Mist) in CDC and NIOSH literature as shorthand.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Non-powered filters were also classified under the HEPA specification, if applicable.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] In 1973, the Los Alamos National Laboratory (LANL) recommended NIOSH use NaCl aerosol to test DM and DFM filters.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Results from those tests showed significant leakage, with efficiency levels measured at around 75% to 90%.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] LANL noted that lead fume would plug the tested filters, increasing the apparent filtration efficiency of the filter.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Historically, respirators in the US had generally been approved by MESA/MSHA/NIOSH under federal regulation 30 CFR 11.[S1] Plans for overhauling Part 11 regulations had been discussed since the late 1980s,[C1] with the first proposed rule being published in the *Federal Register* in August 1987.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] From the start, respirator regulations were planned to be moved from Title 30 to Title 42, Part 84 in the *Code of Federal Regulations*, along with the elimination of joint-approval between NIOSH and MSHA.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Respirator assigned protection factors were also to be updated, along with chemical cartridge requirements.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Under the current revision of Part 84 established in 1995, NIOSH established nine classifications of approved particulate filtering respirators based on a combination of the respirator series and efficiency level.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The second value indicates the minimum efficiency level of the filter.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] When tested according to the protocol established by NIOSH each filter classification must demonstrate the minimum efficiency level indicated below.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] All respirator types are permitted for TB.[C1] Class-100 filters can block asbestos.[CF1][S2] For *N* type filters, a 200 mg load of NaCl is used, with an undefined service time.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] For *R* type filters, a 200 mg of DOP is used, with a defined service time of "one work shift".
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] For *P* type filters, an indefinite amount of DOP is used until filtration efficiency stabilizes.[N2] P100 filters, under 42 CFR part 84, are the only filters permitted to be magenta in color.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] HE (high-efficiency) labeled filters (described in the subsection) are only provided for powered air-purifying respirators.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] HE-marked filters are 99.97% efficient against 0.3 micron particles and are oil-proof.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The following table lists the air flow requirements for NIOSH-approved PAPRs under Part 84.175.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] A study has demonstrated that users carrying out physical work at intensities 80-85% VO2 max "over-breathe" loose-fitting PAPRs and has recommended an increase of air flow to 400 lpm, an approximately two-fold increase over NIOSH-approved values.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Under 42 CFR 84, chemical cartridges and gas mask canisters are defined separately.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] For brevity, only combinations that are different from the TB guide are listed.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] For particulate respirators, while NIOSH designates P100 as filter cartridges that can use the "magenta" color, ANSI designates P100 as "purple", a color which can be seen on some P100 filter cartridges.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] NIOSH is the current regulator of all the respirators in this schedule, under 42 CFR 84.[C1] 'BM' stands for the US Bureau of Mines, the historical regulator of respirators in the United States.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] TC-21C respirator approval numbers for negative-pressure particulate respirators have three digits, in the form: TC-21C-###, while TC-84A respirator approval numbers have four digits, in the form: TC-84A-####.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] NPPTL is the designated publisher of the NIOSH Certified Equipment List, or CEL.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The CEL is a public domain database that details the respirators currently approved by NIOSH, and is ordered separated based on type of respirator, which is designated with a schedule (e.g.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] The CEL was initially released in paper form on September 30, 1993.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] However, due to low usage of the paper CEL, as well as the increasing number of respirators approved by NIOSH, a Microsoft Access-based version of the CEL was released.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Initial releases of the CEL had hose and pressure information for air-line respirators.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] This information had been eliminated due to concerns over users prioritizing the CEL over respirator documentation.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] NIOSH air filtration ratings do not test the fit of a respirator.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] Fit testing is required by OSHA for employers when a hazard is present, and voluntary respirator use under Appendix D is not allowed due to the hazard.[C5] Rules for fit testing are also defined by ANSI Z88.2.
[src:gas-mask/42-cfr-84] A few other jurisdictions use standards similar to the NIOSH scheme to classify mechanical filter respirators.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] A more general term is *sorption*, which covers absorption, adsorption, and ion exchange.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Absorption is a condition in which something takes in another substance.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] In many processes important in technology, the chemical absorption is used in place of the physical process, e.g., absorption of carbon dioxide by sodium hydroxide – such acid-base processes do not follow the Nernst partition law (see: solubility).
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] For some examples of this effect, see liquid-liquid extraction.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] It is possible to extract a solute from one liquid phase to another without a chemical reaction.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Examples of such solutes are noble gases and osmium tetroxide.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] The process of absorption means that a substance captures and transforms energy.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] The absorbent distributes the material it captures throughout whole and adsorbent only distributes it through the surface.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] The process of gas or liquid which penetrate into the body of adsorbent is commonly known as absorption.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] The value of constant KN depends on temperature and is called *partition coefficient*.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] This equation is valid if concentrations are not too large and if the species "x" does not change its form in any of the two phases "1" or "2".
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] If such molecule undergoes association or dissociation then this equation still describes the equilibrium between "x" in both phases, but only for the same form – concentrations of all remaining forms must be calculated by taking into account all the other equilibria.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] In the case of gas absorption, one may calculate its concentration by using, e.g., the Ideal gas law, *c = p/RT*.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] In alternative fashion, one may use partial pressures instead of concentrations.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Absorption is a process that may be chemical (reactive) or physical (non-reactive).
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Chemical absorption or reactive absorption is a chemical reaction between the absorbed and the absorbing substances.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Sometimes it combines with physical absorption.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] This type of absorption depends upon the stoichiometry of the reaction and the concentration of its reactants.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] They may be carried out in different units, with a wide spectrum of phase flow types and interactions.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] In most cases, RA is carried out in plate or packed columns.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Hydrophilic solids, which include many solids of biological origin, can readily absorb water.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] Polar interactions between water and the molecules of the solid favor partition of the water into the solid, which can allow significant absorption of water vapor even in relatively low humidity.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] A fiber (or other hydrophilic material) that has been exposed to the atmosphere will usually contain some water even if it feels dry.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] The water can be driven off by heating in an oven, leading to a measurable decrease in weight, which will gradually be regained if the fiber is returned to a 'normal' atmosphere.
[src:gas-mask/absorption-chemistry] This effect is crucial in the textile industry – where the proportion of a material's weight made up by water is called the *moisture regain*.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:gas-mask/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:gas-mask/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:gas-mask/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:gas-mask/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:gas-mask/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:gas-mask/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:gas-mask/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:gas-mask/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:gas-mask/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:gas-mask/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:gas-mask/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:gas-mask/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:gas-mask/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:gas-mask/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:gas-mask/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:gas-mask/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:gas-mask/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:gas-mask/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:gas-mask/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:gas-mask/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:gas-mask/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:gas-mask/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:gas-mask/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:gas-mask/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:gas-mask/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:gas-mask/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:gas-mask/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:gas-mask/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:gas-mask/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:gas-mask/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:gas-mask/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:gas-mask/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:gas-mask/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Susceptibility to acne is primarily genetic in 80% of cases.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The roles of diet and cigarette smoking in the condition are unclear, and neither cleanliness nor exposure to sunlight are associated with acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In both sexes, hormones called androgens appear to be part of the underlying mechanism, by causing increased production of sebum.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Another common factor is the excessive growth of the bacterium *Cutibacterium acnes*, which is present on the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Treatments for acne are available, including lifestyle changes, medications, and medical procedures.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The most effective medication is isotretinoin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Eating fewer simple carbohydrates such as sugar may minimize the condition.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Treatments applied directly to the affected skin, such as azelaic acid, benzoyl peroxide, and salicylic acid, are commonly used.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Antibiotics and retinoids are available in formulations that are applied to the skin and taken by mouth for the treatment of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] However, resistance to antibiotics may develop as a result of antibiotic therapy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Several types of birth control pills help prevent acne in women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Medical professionals typically reserve isotretinoin pills for severe acne, due to greater potential side effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Early and aggressive treatment of acne is advocated by some in the medical community to decrease the overall long-term impact on individuals.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In 2015, acne affected approximately 633 million people globally, making it the eighth-most common chronic disease worldwide.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne commonly occurs in adolescence and affects an estimated 80–90% of teenagers in the Western world.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Some rural societies report lower rates of acne than industrialized ones.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Children and adults may also be affected before and after puberty.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Although acne becomes less common in adulthood, it persists in nearly half of affected people into their twenties and thirties, and a smaller group continues to have difficulties in their forties.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] There are six main types of acne: blackheads, whiteheads, papules, pustules, nodules, and cysts.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The severity of acne vulgaris (Gr. ἀκμή, "point" + L.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] *vulgaris*, "common") can be classified as mild, moderate, or severe to determine an appropriate treatment regimen.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] There is no universally accepted scale for grading acne severity.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The presence of clogged skin follicles (known as comedones) limited to the face with occasional inflammatory lesions defines mild acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Moderate severity acne is said to occur when a higher number of inflammatory papules and pustules occur on the face, compared to mild cases of acne, and appear on the trunk of the body.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Severe acne is said to occur when nodules (the painful 'bumps' lying under the skin) are the characteristic facial lesions, and involvement of the trunk is extensive.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Large nodules were previously called cysts.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The term *nodulocystic* has been used in the medical literature to describe severe cases of inflammatory acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] True cysts are rare in those with acne, and the term *severe nodular acne* is now the preferred terminology.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Typical features of acne include increased secretion of oily sebum by the skin, microcomedones, comedones, papules, nodules (large papules), pustules, and often results in scarring.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The appearance of acne varies with skin color.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] It may result in psychological and social problems.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne scars are caused by inflammation within the dermis and are estimated to affect 95% of people with acne vulgaris.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Abnormal healing and dermal inflammation create the scar.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Scarring is most likely to take place with severe acne but may occur with any form of acne vulgaris.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne scars are classified based on whether the abnormal healing response following dermal inflammation leads to excess collagen deposition or loss at the site of the acne lesion.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Atrophic acne scars have lost collagen from the healing response and are the most common type of acne scar (accounting for approximately 75% of all acne scars).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Ice-pick scars, boxcar scars, and rolling scars are subtypes of atrophic acne scars.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Boxcar scars are round or ovoid indented scars with sharp borders and vary in size from 1.5–4 mm across.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Ice-pick scars are narrow (less than 2 mm across), deep scars that extend into the dermis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Rolling scars are broader than ice-pick and boxcar scars (4–5 mm across) and have a wave-like pattern of depth in the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Hypertrophic scars are uncommon and are characterized by increased collagen content after the abnormal healing response.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] They are described as firm and raised from the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Hypertrophic scars remain within the original margins of the wound, whereas keloid scars can form scar tissue outside of these borders.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Keloid scars from acne occur more often in men and people with darker skin, and usually occur on the trunk of the body.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] After an inflamed nodular acne lesion resolves, it is common for the skin to darken in that area, which is known as postinflammatory hyperpigmentation (PIH).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The inflammation stimulates specialized pigment-producing skin cells (known as melanocytes) to produce more melanin pigment, which leads to the skin's darkened appearance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] PIH occurs more frequently in people with darker skin color.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Pigmented scar is a common term used for PIH, but is misleading as it suggests the color change is permanent.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Often, PIH can be prevented by avoiding any aggravation of the nodule and can fade with time.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] However, untreated PIH can last for months, years, or even be permanent if deeper layers of skin are affected.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Even minimal skin exposure to the sun's ultraviolet rays can sustain hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Daily use of SPF 15 or higher sunscreen can minimize such a risk.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Whitening agents like azelaic acid, arbutin or else may be used to improve hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Risk factors for the development of acne, other than genetics, have not been conclusively identified.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Possible secondary contributors include hormones, infections, diet, and stress.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Studies investigating the impact of smoking on the incidence and severity of acne have been inconclusive.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Cleanliness (hygiene) and sunlight are not associated with acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne appears to be highly heritable; genetics explain 81% of the variation in the population.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Studies performed in affected twins and first-degree relatives further demonstrate the strongly inherited nature of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne susceptibility is likely due to the influence of multiple genes, as the disease does not follow a classic (Mendelian) inheritance pattern.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] These gene candidates include certain variations in tumor necrosis factor-alpha (TNF-alpha), IL-1 alpha, and CYP1A1 genes, among others.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The 308 G/A single nucleotide polymorphism variation in the gene for TNF is associated with an increased risk for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne can be a feature of rare genetic disorders such as Apert's syndrome.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Severe acne may be associated with XYY syndrome.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Hormonal activity, such as occurs during menstrual cycles and puberty, may contribute to the formation of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] During puberty, an increase in sex hormones called androgens causes the skin follicle glands to grow larger and make more oily sebum.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The androgen hormones testosterone, dihydrotestosterone (DHT), and dehydroepiandrosterone (DHEA) are all linked to acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] High levels of growth hormone (GH) and insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF-1) are also associated with worsened acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Both androgens and IGF-1 seem to be essential for acne to occur, as acne does not develop in individuals with complete androgen insensitivity syndrome (CAIS) or Laron syndrome (insensitivity to GH, resulting in very low IGF-1 levels).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Medical conditions that commonly cause a high-androgen state, such as polycystic ovary syndrome, congenital adrenal hyperplasia, and androgen-secreting tumors, can cause acne in affected individuals.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Conversely, people who lack androgenic hormones or are insensitive to the effects of androgens rarely have acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Pregnancy can increase androgen levels, and consequently, oily sebum synthesis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne can be a side effect of testosterone replacement therapy or anabolic steroid use.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Over-the-counter bodybuilding and dietary supplements often contain illegally added anabolic steroids.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The anaerobic bacterial species *Cutibacterium acnes* (formerly *Propionibacterium acnes*) contributes to the development of acne, but its exact role is not well understood.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] There are specific sub-strains of *C. acnes* associated with normal skin and others with moderate or severe inflammatory acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] It is unclear whether these undesirable strains evolve on-site or are acquired, or possibly both depending on the person.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] These strains have the capability of changing, perpetuating, or adapting to the abnormal cycle of inflammation, oil production, and inadequate sloughing of dead skin cells from acne pores.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Some studies have explored a possible link between Demodex mites and acne, though findings remain inconclusive.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] It is unclear whether eradication of the mite improves acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] High-glycemic-load diets have been found to have different degrees of effect on acne severity.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Multiple randomized controlled trials and nonrandomized studies have found a lower-glycemic-load diet to be effective in reducing acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] There is weak observational evidence suggesting that dairy milk consumption is positively associated with a higher frequency and severity of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Milk contains whey protein and hormones such as bovine IGF-1 and precursors of dihydrotestosterone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Studies suggest these components promote the effects of insulin and IGF-1 and thereby increase the production of androgen hormones, sebum, and promote the formation of comedones.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Available evidence does not support a link between eating chocolate or salt and acne severity.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Few studies have examined the relationship between obesity and acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Vitamin B12 may trigger skin outbreaks similar to acne (acneiform eruptions), or worsen existing acne when taken in doses exceeding the recommended daily intake.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] There are few high-quality studies to demonstrate that stress causes or worsens acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Despite being controversial, some research indicates that increased acne severity is associated with high stress levels in certain contexts, such as hormonal changes seen in premenstrual syndrome.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Some individuals experience severe intensification of their acne when they are exposed to hot humid climates; this is due to bacteria and fungus thriving in warm, moist environments.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] This climate-induced acne exacerbation has been termed tropical acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Mechanical obstruction of skin follicles with helmets or chinstraps can worsen pre-existing acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] However, acne caused by mechanical obstruction is technically not acne vulgaris, but another acneiform eruption known as acne mechanica.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Several medications can also worsen pre-existing acne; this condition is the acne medicamentosa form of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Examples of such medications include lithium, hydantoin, isoniazid, glucocorticoids, iodides, bromides, and testosterone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] When acne medicamentosa is specifically caused by anabolic–androgenic steroids it can simply be referred to as steroid acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Genetically susceptible individuals can get acne breakouts as a result of polymorphous light eruption; a condition triggered by sunlight and artificial UV light exposure.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] This form of acne is called Acne aestivalis and is specifically caused by intense UVA light exposure.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Affected individuals usually experience seasonal acne breakouts on their upper arms, shoulder girdle, back, and chest.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The breakouts typically occur one-to-three days after exposure to intense UVA radiation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Unlike other forms of acne, the condition spares the face; this could possibly be a result of the pathogenesis of polymorphous light eruption, in which areas of the skin that are *newly* exposed to intense ultraviolet radiation are affected.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Since faces are typically left uncovered at all stages of life, there is little-to-no likelihood for an eruption to appear there.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Studies show that both polymorphous light eruption outbreaks and the acne aestivalis breakout response can be prevented by topical antioxidants combined with the application of a broad spectrum sunscreen.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne vulgaris is a chronic skin disease of the pilosebaceous unit and develops due to blockages in the skin's hair follicles.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Traditionally seen as a disease of adolescence, acne vulgaris is also observed in adults, including post-menopausal women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne vulgaris manifested in adult female is called *adult female acne* (AFA), defined as a chronic inflammatory disease of the pilosebaceous unit.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The earliest pathologic change is the formation of a plug (a microcomedone), which is driven primarily by excessive growth, reproduction, and accumulation of skin cells in the hair follicle.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In healthy skin, the skin cells that have died come up to the surface and exit the pore of the hair follicle.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In people with acne, the increased production of oily sebum causes the dead skin cells to stick together.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The accumulation of dead skin cell debris and oily sebum blocks the pore of the hair follicle, thus forming the microcomedone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The *C. acnes* biofilm within the hair follicle worsens this process.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] If the microcomedone is superficial within the hair follicle, the skin pigment melanin is exposed to air, resulting in its oxidation and dark appearance (known as a blackhead or open comedo).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In contrast, if the microcomedone occurs deep within the hair follicle, this causes the formation of a whitehead (known as a closed comedo).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The main hormonal driver of oily sebum production in the skin is dihydrotestosterone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Another androgenic hormone responsible for increased sebaceous gland activity is DHEA-S.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The adrenal glands secrete higher amounts of DHEA-S during adrenarche (a stage of puberty), and this leads to an increase in sebum production.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In a sebum-rich skin environment, the naturally occurring and largely commensal skin bacterium *C. acnes* readily grows and can cause inflammation within and around the follicle due to activation of the innate immune system.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] *C. acnes* triggers skin inflammation in acne by increasing the production of several pro-inflammatory chemical signals (such as IL-1α, IL-8, TNF-α, and LTB4); IL-1α is essential to comedo formation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] This inflammatory cascade typically leads to the formation of inflammatory acne lesions, including papules, infected pustules, or nodules.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] If the inflammatory reaction is severe, the follicle can break into the deeper layers of the dermis and subcutaneous tissue and cause the formation of deep nodules.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The involvement of AP-1 in the aforementioned inflammatory cascade activates matrix metalloproteinases, which contribute to local tissue destruction and scar formation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Along with the bacteria *C. acnes*, the bacterial species *Staphylococcus epidermidis* (*S. epidermidis*) also takes a part in the physiopathology of acne vulgaris.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The proliferation of *S. epidermidis* with *C. acnes* causes the formation of biofilms, which blocks the hair follicles and pores, creating an anaerobic environment under the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] This enables for increased growth of both *C. acnes* and *S. epidermidis* under the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The proliferation of *C. acnes* causes the formation of biofilms and a biofilm matrix, making it even harder to treat the acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Acne vulgaris is diagnosed based on a medical professional's clinical judgment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The evaluation of a person with suspected acne should include taking a detailed medical history about a family history of acne, a review of medications taken, signs or symptoms of excessive production of androgen hormones, cortisol, and growth hormone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Comedones (blackheads and whiteheads) must be present to diagnose acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] In their absence, an appearance similar to that of acne would suggest a different skin disorder.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Microcomedones (the precursor to blackheads and whiteheads) are not visible to the naked eye when inspecting the skin and require a microscope to be seen.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Many features may indicate that a person's acne vulgaris is sensitive to hormonal influences.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Historical and physical clues that may suggest hormone-sensitive acne include onset between ages 20 and 30; worsening the week before a woman's period; acne lesions predominantly over the jawline and chin; and inflammatory/nodular acne lesions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Several scales exist to grade the severity of acne vulgaris, but disagreement persists about the ideal one for diagnostic use.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Cook's acne grading scale uses photographs to grade severity from 0 to 8, with higher numbers representing more severe acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] This scale was the first to use a standardized photographic protocol to assess acne severity; since its creation in 1979, the scale has undergone several revisions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The Leeds acne grading technique counts acne lesions on the face, back, and chest and categorizes them as inflammatory or non-inflammatory.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Leeds scores range from 0 (least severe) to 10 (most severe) though modified scales have a maximum score of 12.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The Pillsbury acne grading scale classifies the severity of the acne from grade 1 (least severe) to grade 4 (most severe).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Many skin conditions can mimic acne vulgaris, and these are collectively known as acneiform eruptions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Such conditions include angiofibromas, epidermal cysts, flat warts, folliculitis, keratosis pilaris, milia, perioral dermatitis, and rosacea, among others.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Age is one factor that may help distinguish between these disorders.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Skin disorders such as perioral dermatitis and keratosis pilaris can appear similar to acne but tend to occur more frequently in childhood.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Rosacea tends to occur more frequently in older adults.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Facial redness triggered by heat or the consumption of alcohol or spicy food is also more suggestive of rosacea.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] The presence of comedones helps health professionals differentiate acne from skin disorders that are similar in appearance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p01] Chloracne and occupational acne due to exposure to certain chemicals & industrial compounds, may look very similar to acne vulgaris.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Many different treatments exist for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] These include alpha hydroxy acid, anti-androgen medications, antibiotics, antiseborrheic medications, azelaic acid, benzoyl peroxide, hormonal treatments, keratolytic soaps, nicotinamide (niacinamide), retinoids, and salicylic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne treatments work in at least four different ways, including the following: reducing inflammation, hormonal manipulation, killing *C. acnes*, and normalizing skin cell shedding and sebum production in the pore to prevent blockage.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Typical treatments include topical therapies such as antibiotics, benzoyl peroxide, and retinoids, and systemic therapies, including antibiotics, hormonal agents, and oral retinoids.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Recommended therapies for first-line use in acne vulgaris treatment include topical retinoids, benzoyl peroxide, and topical or oral antibiotics.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Procedures such as light therapy and laser therapy are not first-line treatments and typically have only an add on role due to their high cost and limited evidence.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Blue light therapy is of unclear benefit.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Medications for acne target the early stages of comedo formation and are generally ineffective for visible skin lesions; acne generally improves between eight and twelve weeks after starting therapy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] People often view acne as a short-term condition, some expecting it to disappear after puberty.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] This misconception can lead to depending on self-management or problems with long-term adherence to treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Communicating the long-term nature of the condition and better access to reliable information about acne can help people know what to expect from treatments.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In general, it is recommended that people with acne do not wash affected skin more than twice daily.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The application of a fragrance-free moisturizer to sensitive and acne-prone skin may reduce irritation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Skin irritation from acne medications typically peaks at two weeks after onset of use and tends to improve with continued use.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermatologists recommend using cosmetic products that specifically say non-comedogenic, oil-free, and will not clog pores.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne vulgaris patients, even those with oily skin, should moisturize in order to support the skin's moisture barrier since skin barrier dysfunction may contribute to acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Moisturizers, especially ceramide-containing moisturizers, as an adjunct therapy are particularly helpful for the dry skin and irritation that commonly results from topical acne treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Studies show that ceramide-containing moisturizers are important for optimal skin care; they enhance acne therapy adherence and complement existing acne therapies.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In a study where acne patients used 1.2% clindamycin phosphate / 2.5% benzoyl peroxide gel in the morning and applied a micronized 0.05% tretinoin gel in the evening the overwhelming majority of patients experienced no cutaneous adverse events throughout the study.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It was concluded that using ceramide cleanser and ceramide moisturizing cream caused the favorable tolerability, did not interfere with the treatment efficacy, and improved adherence to the regimen.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The importance of preserving the acidic mantle and its barrier functions is widely accepted in the scientific community.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Thus, maintaining a pH in the range 4.5 – 5.5 is essential in order to keep the skin surface in its optimal, healthy conditions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Causal relationship is rarely observed with diet/nutrition and dermatologic conditions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Rather, associations have been found between diet and outcomes including disease severity and the number of conditions experienced by a patient.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Evidence is emerging in support of medical nutrition therapy as a way of reducing the severity and incidence of dermatologic diseases, including acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Researchers observed a link between high glycemic index diets and acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermatologists also recommend a diet low in simple sugars as a method of improving acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] As of 2014, the available evidence is insufficient to use milk restriction for this purpose.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Benzoyl peroxide (BPO) is a first-line treatment for mild and moderate acne due to its effectiveness and mild side-effects (mainly skin irritation).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In the skin follicle, benzoyl peroxide kills *C. acnes* by oxidizing its proteins through the formation of oxygen free radicals and benzoic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] These free radicals likely interfere with the bacterium's metabolism and ability to make proteins.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Additionally, benzoyl peroxide is mildly effective at breaking down comedones and inhibiting inflammation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Combination products use benzoyl peroxide with a topical antibiotic or retinoid, such as benzoyl peroxide/clindamycin and benzoyl peroxide/adapalene, respectively.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical benzoyl peroxide is effective at treating acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Side effects include increased skin photosensitivity, dryness, redness, and occasional peeling.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Sunscreen use is often advised during treatment, to prevent sunburn.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Lower concentrations of benzoyl peroxide are just as effective as higher concentrations in treating acne but are associated with fewer side effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Unlike antibiotics, benzoyl peroxide does not appear to generate bacterial antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Retinoids are medications that reduce inflammation, normalize the follicle cell life cycle, and reduce sebum production.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] They are structurally related to vitamin A.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Studies show dermatologists and primary care doctors underprescribe them for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The retinoids appear to influence the cell life cycle in the follicle lining.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] This helps prevent the accumulation of skin cells within the hair follicle that can create a blockage.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] They are a first-line acne treatment, especially for people with dark-colored skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Retinoids are known to lead to faster improvement of postinflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical retinoids include adapalene, retinol, retinaldehyde, isotretinoin, tazarotene, trifarotene, and tretinoin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] They often cause an initial flare-up of acne and facial flushing and can cause significant skin irritation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Generally speaking, retinoids increase the skin's sensitivity to sunlight and are therefore recommended for use at night.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Tretinoin is the least expensive of the topical retinoids and is the most irritating to the skin, whereas adapalene is the least irritating but costs significantly more.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Most formulations of tretinoin are incompatible for use with benzoyl peroxide.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Tazarotene is the most effective and expensive topical retinoid but is usually not as well tolerated.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In 2019, a tazarotene lotion formulation, marketed to be a less irritating option, was approved by the FDA.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Retinol is a form of vitamin A that has similar but milder effects and is present in many over-the-counter moisturizers and other topical products.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Isotretinoin is an oral retinoid that is very effective for both severe nodular acne and moderate acne that is stubborn to other treatments.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] One to two months of use is typically adequate to see improvement.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne often resolves completely or is much milder after a 4–6 month course of oral isotretinoin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] After a single round of treatment, about 80% of people report an improvement, with more than 50% reporting complete remission.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] About 20% of people require a second course, but 80% of those report improvement, resulting in a cumulative 96% efficacy rate.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] There are concerns that isotretinoin is linked to adverse effects, depression, suicidality, and anemia.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] There is no clear evidence to support some of these claims.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Isotretinoin has been found in some studies to be superior to antibiotics or placebo in reducing acne lesions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, a 2018 review comparing inflammatory lesions after treatment with antibiotics or isotretinoin found no difference.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The frequency of adverse events was about twice as high with isotretinoin use, although these were mostly dryness-related events.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] No increased risk of suicide or depression was conclusively found.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Medical authorities strictly regulate isotretinoin use in women of childbearing age due to its known harmful effects in pregnancy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] For such a woman to be considered a candidate for isotretinoin, she must have a confirmed negative pregnancy test and use an effective form of birth control.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In 2008, the United States started the iPLEDGE program to prevent isotretinoin use during pregnancy. iPLEDGE requires the woman to have two negative pregnancy tests and to use two types of birth control for at least one month before isotretinoin therapy begins and one month afterward.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The effectiveness of the iPLEDGE program is controversial due to continued instances of contraception nonadherence.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] People may apply antibiotics to the skin or take them orally to treat acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] They work by killing *C. acnes* and reducing inflammation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Although multiple guidelines call for healthcare providers to reduce the rates of prescribed oral antibiotics, many providers do not follow this guidance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Oral antibiotics remain the most commonly prescribed systemic therapy for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Widespread broad-spectrum antibiotic overuse for acne has led to higher rates of antibiotic-resistant *C. acnes* strains worldwide, especially to the commonly used tetracycline (e.g., doxycycline) and macrolide antibiotics (e.g., topical erythromycin).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Therefore, dermatologists prefer antibiotics as part of combination therapy and not for use alone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Commonly used antibiotics, either applied to the skin or taken orally, include clindamycin, erythromycin, metronidazole, sulfacetamide, and tetracyclines (e.g., doxycycline or minocycline).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Doxycycline 40 milligrams daily (low-dose) appears to have similar efficacy to 100 milligrams daily and has fewer gastrointestinal side effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, low-dose doxycycline is not FDA-approved for the treatment of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Antibiotics applied to the skin are typically used for mild to moderately severe acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Oral antibiotics are generally more effective than topical antibiotics and produce faster resolution of inflammatory acne lesions than topical applications.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The *Global Alliance to Improve Outcomes in Acne* recommends that topical and oral antibiotics are not used together.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Oral antibiotics are recommended for no longer than three months, as antibiotic courses exceeding this duration are associated with the development of antibiotic resistance and show no clear benefit over shorter durations.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] If long-term oral antibiotics beyond three months are used, then it is recommended that benzoyl peroxide or a retinoid be used at the same time to limit the risk of *C. acnes* developing antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The antibiotic dapsone is effective against inflammatory acne when applied to the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is generally not a first-line choice due to its higher cost and a lack of clear superiority over other antibiotics.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical dapsone is sometimes a preferred therapy in women or for people with sensitive or darker-toned skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is not recommended for use with benzoyl peroxide due to the risk of causing yellow-orange skin discoloration with this combination.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Minocycline is an effective acne treatment, but it is not a first-line antibiotic due to a lack of evidence that it is better than other treatments and concerns about its safety compared to other tetracyclines.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Sarecycline is the most recent oral antibiotic developed specifically for the treatment of acne, and it is FDA-approved for the treatment of moderate to severe inflammatory acne in patients nine years of age and older.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is a narrow-spectrum tetracycline antibiotic that exhibits the necessary antibacterial activity against pathogens related to acne vulgaris and a low propensity for inducing antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In clinical trials, sarecycline demonstrated clinical efficacy in reducing inflammatory acne lesions as early as three weeks and reduced truncal (back and chest) acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In women, the use of combined birth control pills can improve acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] These medications contain an estrogen and a progestin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] They work by decreasing the production of androgen hormones by the ovaries and by decreasing the free and hence biologically active fractions of androgens, resulting in lowered skin production of sebum and consequently reduce acne severity.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] First-generation progestins such as norethindrone and norgestrel have androgenic properties and may worsen acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Although oral estrogens decrease IGF-1 levels in some situations, which could theoretically improve acne symptoms, combined birth control pills do not appear to affect IGF-1 levels in fertile women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Cyproterone acetate-containing birth control pills seem to decrease total and free IGF-1 levels.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Combinations containing third- or fourth-generation progestins, including desogestrel, dienogest, drospirenone, or norgestimate, as well as birth control pills containing cyproterone acetate or chlormadinone acetate, are preferred for women with acne due to their stronger antiandrogenic effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Studies have shown a 40 to 70% reduction in acne lesions with combined birth control pills.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] A 2014 review found that oral antibiotics appear to be somewhat more effective than birth control pills at reducing the number of inflammatory acne lesions at three months.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, the two therapies are approximately equal in efficacy at six months for decreasing the number of inflammatory, non-inflammatory, and total acne lesions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The authors of the analysis suggested that birth control pills may be a preferred first-line acne treatment over oral antibiotics in certain women due to similar efficacy at six months and a lack of associated antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In contrast to combined birth control pills, progestogen-only birth control forms that contain androgenic progestins have been associated with worsened acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Antiandrogens such as cyproterone acetate and spironolactone can successfully treat acne, especially in women with signs of excessive androgen production, such as increased hairiness or skin production of sebum, or scalp hair loss.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Spironolactone is an effective treatment for acne in adult women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Unlike combined birth control pills, it is not approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration for this purpose.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Spironolactone is an aldosterone antagonist and is a useful acne treatment due to its ability to additionally block the androgen receptor at higher doses.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Alone or in combination with a birth control pill, spironolactone has shown a 33 to 85% reduction in acne lesions in women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The effectiveness of spironolactone for acne appears to be dose-dependent.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] High-dose cyproterone acetate alone reportedly decreases acne symptoms in women by 75 to 90% within three months.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is usually combined with an estrogen to avoid menstrual irregularities and estrogen deficiency.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The medication appears to be effective in the treatment of acne in males, with one study finding that a high dosage reduced inflammatory acne lesions by 73%.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, spironolactone and cyproterone acetate's side effects in males, such as gynecomastia, sexual dysfunction, and decreased bone mineral density, generally make their use for male acne impractical.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Pregnant and lactating women should not receive antiandrogens for their acne due to a possibility of birth disorders such as hypospadias and feminization of male babies.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Women who are sexually active and who can or may become pregnant should use an effective method of contraception to prevent pregnancy while taking an antiandrogen.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Antiandrogens are often combined with birth control pills for this reason, which can result in additive efficacy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The FDA added a black-box warning to spironolactone about possible tumor risks based on preclinical research with very high doses (>100-fold clinical doses) and cautioned that unnecessary use of the medication should be avoided.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, several large epidemiological studies subsequently found no greater risk of tumors in association with spironolactone in humans.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Conversely, strong associations of cyproterone acetate with certain brain tumors have been discovered and its use has been restricted.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The brain tumor risk with cyproterone acetate is due to its strong progestogenic actions and is not related to antiandrogenic activity nor shared by other antiandrogens.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Flutamide, a pure antagonist of the androgen receptor, is effective in treating acne in women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It appears to reduce acne symptoms by 80 to 90% even at low doses, with several studies showing complete acne clearance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In one study, flutamide decreased acne scores by 80% within three months, whereas spironolactone decreased symptoms by only 40% in the same period.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In a large long-term study, 97% of women reported satisfaction with the control of their acne with flutamide.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Although effective, flutamide has a risk of serious liver toxicity, and cases of death in women taking even low doses of the medication to treat androgen-dependent skin and hair conditions have occurred.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] As such, the use of flutamide for acne has become increasingly limited, and it has been argued that continued use of flutamide for such purposes is unethical.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Bicalutamide, a pure androgen receptor antagonist with the same mechanism as flutamide and with comparable or superior antiandrogenic efficacy but with a far lower risk of liver toxicity, is an alternative option to flutamide in the treatment of androgen-dependent skin and hair conditions in women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Clascoterone is a topical antiandrogen that has demonstrated effectiveness in the treatment of acne in both males and females and was approved for clinical use for this indication in August 2020.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It has shown no systemic absorption or associated antiandrogenic side effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In a small direct head-to-head comparison, clascoterone showed greater effectiveness than topical isotretinoin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] 5α-Reductase inhibitors such as finasteride and dutasteride may be useful for the treatment of acne in both males and females but have not been adequately evaluated for this purpose.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Moreover, 5α-reductase inhibitors have a strong potential for producing birth defects in male babies and this limits their use in women.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] However, 5α-reductase inhibitors are frequently used to treat excessive facial/body hair in women and can be combined with birth control pills to prevent pregnancy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] There is no evidence as of 2010 to support the use of cimetidine or ketoconazole in the treatment of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Hormone therapy is effective for acne both in women with hyperandrogenism and in women with normal androgen levels.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Azelaic acid is effective for mild to moderate acne when applied topically at a 15–20% concentration.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Treatment twice daily for six months is necessary, and is as effective as topical benzoyl peroxide 5%, isotretinoin 0.05%, and erythromycin 2%.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Azelaic acid is an effective acne treatment due to its ability to reduce skin cell accumulation in the follicle and its antibacterial and anti-inflammatory properties.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It has a slight skin-lightening effect due to its ability to inhibit melanin synthesis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Therefore, it is useful in treating individuals with acne who are also affected by post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is less effective and more expensive than retinoids.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Azelaic acid also led to worse treatment response when compared to benzoyl peroxide.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] When compared to tretinoin, azelaic acid makes little or no treatment response.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Salicylic acid is a topically applied beta-hydroxy acid that stops bacteria from reproducing and has keratolytic properties.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is less effective than retinoid therapy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Salicylic acid opens obstructed skin pores and promotes the shedding of epithelial skin cells.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dry skin is the most commonly seen side effect with topical application, though darkening of the skin can occur in individuals with darker skin types.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical and oral preparations of nicotinamide (the amide form of vitamin B3) are alternative medical treatments.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical and oral preparations of zinc are suggested treatments for acne; evidence to support their use for this purpose is limited.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Zinc's capacities to reduce inflammation and sebum production as well as inhibit *C. acnes* growth are its proposed mechanisms for improving acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Antihistamines may improve symptoms among those already taking isotretinoin due to their anti-inflammatory properties and their ability to suppress sebum production.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Hydroquinone lightens the skin when applied topically by inhibiting tyrosinase, the enzyme responsible for converting the amino acid tyrosine to the skin pigment melanin, and is used to treat acne-associated post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] By interfering with the production of melanin in the epidermis, hydroquinone leads to less hyperpigmentation as darkened skin cells are naturally shed over time.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Improvement in skin hyperpigmentation is typically seen within six months when used twice daily.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Hydroquinone is ineffective for hyperpigmentation affecting deeper layers of skin such as the dermis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The use of a sunscreen with SPF 15 or higher in the morning with reapplication every two hours is recommended when using hydroquinone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Its application only to affected areas lowers the risk of lightening the color of normal skin but can lead to a temporary ring of lightened skin around the hyperpigmented area.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Hydroquinone is generally well-tolerated; side effects are typically mild (e.g., skin irritation) and occur with the use of a higher than the recommended 4% concentration.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Most preparations contain the preservative sodium metabisulfite, which has been linked to rare cases of allergic reactions, including anaphylaxis and severe asthma exacerbations in susceptible people.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In extremely rare cases, the frequent and improper application of high-dose hydroquinone has been associated with a systemic condition known as exogenous ochronosis (skin discoloration and connective tissue damage from the accumulation of homogentisic acid).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Combination therapy—using medications of different classes together, each with a different mechanism of action—has been demonstrated to be a more effective approach to acne treatment than monotherapy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The use of topical benzoyl peroxide and antibiotics together is more effective than antibiotics alone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Similarly, using a topical retinoid with an antibiotic clears acne lesions faster than the use of antibiotics alone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Frequently used combinations include the following: antibiotic and benzoyl peroxide, antibiotic and topical retinoid, or topical retinoid and benzoyl peroxide.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermatologists generally prefer combining benzoyl peroxide with a retinoid over the combination of a topical antibiotic with a retinoid.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Both regimens are effective, but benzoyl peroxide does not lead to antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Although sebaceous gland activity in the skin increases during the late stages of pregnancy, pregnancy has not been reliably associated with worsened acne severity.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In general, topically applied medications are considered the first-line approach to acne treatment during pregnancy, as they have little systemic absorption and are therefore unlikely to harm a developing fetus.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Highly recommended therapies include topically applied benzoyl peroxide (pregnancy category C) and azelaic acid (category B).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Prolonged use of salicylic acid over significant areas of the skin or under occlusive (sealed) dressings is not recommended as these methods increase systemic absorption and the potential for fetal harm.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Tretinoin (category C) and adapalene (category C) are very poorly absorbed, but certain studies have suggested teratogenic effects in the first trimester.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The data examining the association between maternal topical retinoid exposure in the first trimester of pregnancy and adverse pregnancy outcomes is limited.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] A systematic review of observational studies concluded that such exposure does not appear to increase the risk of major birth defects, miscarriages, stillbirths, premature births, or low birth weight.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Similarly, in studies examining the effects of topical retinoids during pregnancy, fetal harm has not been seen in the second and third trimesters.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Nevertheless, since rare harms from topical retinoids are not ruled out, they are not recommended for use during pregnancy due to persistent safety concerns.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Retinoids contraindicated for use during pregnancy include the topical retinoid tazarotene, and oral retinoids isotretinoin and acitretin (all category X).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Spironolactone is relatively contraindicated for use during pregnancy due to its antiandrogen effects.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Finasteride is not recommended as it is highly teratogenic.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Topical antibiotics deemed safe during pregnancy include clindamycin, erythromycin, and metronidazole (all category B), due to negligible systemic absorption.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Nadifloxacin and dapsone (category C) are other topical antibiotics that may be used to treat acne in pregnant women but have received less study.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] No adverse fetal events have been reported from the topical use of dapsone.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] If retinoids are used there is a high risk of abnormalities occurring in the developing fetus; women of childbearing age are therefore required to use effective birth control if retinoids are used to treat acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Oral antibiotics deemed safe for pregnancy (all category B) include azithromycin, cephalosporins, and penicillins.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Tetracyclines (category D) are contraindicated during pregnancy as they are known to deposit in developing fetal teeth, resulting in yellow discoloration and thinned tooth enamel.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Their use during pregnancy has been associated with the development of acute fatty liver of pregnancy and is further avoided for this reason.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Limited evidence supports comedo extraction, but it is an option for comedones that do not improve with standard treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Another procedure for immediate relief is the injection of a corticosteroid into an inflamed acne comedo.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Electrocautery and electrofulguration are effective alternative treatments for comedones.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Light therapy is a treatment method that involves delivering certain specific wavelengths of light to an area of skin affected by acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Both regular and laser light have been used.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The evidence for light therapy as a treatment for acne is weak and inconclusive.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Various light therapies appear to provide a short-term benefit, but data for long-term outcomes, and outcomes in those with severe acne, are sparse; it may have a role for individuals whose acne has been resistant to topical medications.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] A 2016 meta-analysis was unable to conclude whether light therapies were more beneficial than placebo or no treatment, nor the duration of benefit.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] When regular light is used immediately following the application of a sensitizing substance to the skin such as aminolevulinic acid or methyl aminolevulinate, the treatment is referred to as photodynamic therapy (PDT).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] PDT has the most supporting evidence of all light therapy modalities.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] PDT treats acne by using various forms of light (e.g., blue light or red light) that preferentially target the pilosebaceous unit.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Once the light activates the sensitizing substance, this generates free radicals and reactive oxygen species in the skin, which purposefully damage the sebaceous glands and kill *C. acnes* bacteria.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Many different types of nonablative lasers (i.e., lasers that do not vaporize the top layer of the skin but rather induce a physiologic response in the skin from the light) have been used to treat acne, including those that use infrared wavelengths of light.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Ablative lasers (such as CO2 and fractional types) have also been used to treat active acne and its scars.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] When ablative lasers are used, the treatment is often referred to as laser resurfacing because, as mentioned previously, the entire upper layers of the skin are vaporized.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Ablative lasers are associated with higher rates of adverse effects compared with non-ablative lasers, with examples being post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation, persistent facial redness, and persistent pain.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Physiologically, certain wavelengths of light, used with or without accompanying topical chemicals, are thought to kill bacteria and decrease the size and activity of the glands that produce sebum.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Disadvantages of light therapy can include its cost, the need for multiple visits, the time required to complete the procedure(s), and pain associated with some of the treatment modalities.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Typical side effects include skin peeling, temporary reddening of the skin, swelling, and post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermabrasion is an effective therapeutic procedure for reducing the appearance of superficial atrophic scars of the boxcar and rolling varieties.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Ice-pick scars do not respond well to treatment with dermabrasion due to their depth.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The procedure is painful and has many potential side effects such as skin sensitivity to sunlight, redness, and decreased pigmentation of the skin.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermabrasion has fallen out of favor with the introduction of laser resurfacing.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Unlike dermabrasion, there is no evidence that microdermabrasion is an effective treatment for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermal or subcutaneous fillers are substances injected into the skin to improve the appearance of acne scars.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Fillers are used to increase natural collagen production in the skin and to increase skin volume and decrease the depth of acne scars.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Examples of fillers used for this purpose include hyaluronic acid; poly(methyl methacrylate) microspheres with collagen; human and bovine collagen derivatives, and fat harvested from the person's own body (autologous fat transfer).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Microneedling is a procedure in which an instrument with multiple rows of tiny needles is rolled over the skin to elicit a wound healing response and stimulate collagen production to reduce the appearance of atrophic acne scars in people with darker skin color.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Notable adverse effects of microneedling include post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation and tram track scarring (described as discrete slightly raised scars in a linear distribution similar to a tram track).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The latter is thought to be primarily attributable to improper technique by the practitioner, including the use of excessive pressure or inappropriately large needles.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Subcision is useful for the treatment of superficial atrophic acne scars and involves the use of a small needle to loosen the fibrotic adhesions that result in the depressed appearance of the scar.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Chemical peels can be used to reduce the appearance of acne scars.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Mild peels include those using glycolic acid, lactic acid, salicylic acid, Jessner's solution, or a lower concentration (20%) of trichloroacetic acid.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] These peels only affect the epidermal layer of the skin and can be useful in the treatment of superficial acne scars as well as skin pigmentation changes from inflammatory acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Higher concentrations of trichloroacetic acid (30–40%) are considered to be medium-strength peels and affect the skin as deep as the papillary dermis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Formulations of trichloroacetic acid concentrated to 50% or more are considered to be deep chemical peels.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Medium-strength and deep-strength chemical peels are more effective for deeper atrophic scars but are more likely to cause side effects such as skin pigmentation changes, infection, and small white superficial cysts known as milia.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Researchers are investigating complementary therapies as treatment for people with acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Low-quality evidence suggests topical application of tea tree oil or bee venom may reduce the total number of skin lesions in those with acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Tea tree oil appears to be approximately as effective as benzoyl peroxide or salicylic acid but is associated with allergic contact dermatitis.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Proposed mechanisms for tea tree oil's anti-acne effects include antibacterial action against *C. acnes* and anti-inflammatory properties.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Numerous other plant-derived therapies have demonstrated positive effects against acne (e.g., basil oil; oligosaccharides from seaweed; however, few well-done studies have examined their use for this purpose.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] There is a lack of high-quality evidence for the use of acupuncture, herbal medicine, or cupping therapy for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Many over-the-counter treatments in many forms are available, which are often known as cosmeceuticals.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Certain types of makeup may be useful to mask acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In those with oily skin, a water-based product is often preferred.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne usually improves around the age of 20 but may persist into adulthood.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Rare complications from acne or its treatment include the formation of pyogenic granulomas, osteoma cutis, and acne with facial edema.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Early and aggressive treatment of acne is advocated by some in the medical community to reduce the chances of these poor outcomes.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] There is good evidence to support the idea that acne and associated scarring negatively affect a person's psychological state, worsen mood, lower self-esteem, and are associated with a higher risk of anxiety disorders, depression, and suicidal thoughts.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Misperceptions about acne's causative and aggravating factors are common, and people with acne often blame themselves, and others often blame those with acne for their condition.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Such blame can worsen the affected person's sense of self-esteem.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Until the 20th century, even among dermatologists, the list of causes was believed to include excessive sexual thoughts and masturbation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Dermatology's association with sexually transmitted infections, especially syphilis, contributed to the stigma.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Another psychological complication of acne vulgaris is acne excoriée, which occurs when a person persistently picks and scratches pimples, irrespective of the severity of their acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] This can lead to significant scarring, changes in the affected person's skin pigmentation, and a cyclic worsening of the affected person's anxiety about their appearance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Globally, acne affects approximately 650 million people, or about 9.4% of the population, as of 2010.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It affects nearly 90% of people in Western societies during their teenage years, but can occur before adolescence and may persist into adulthood.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] While acne that first develops between the ages of 21 and 25 is uncommon, it affects 54% of women and 40% of men older than 25 years of age and has a lifetime prevalence of 85%.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] About 20% of those affected have moderate or severe cases.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] It is slightly more common in females than males (9.8% versus 9.0%).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In those over 40 years old, 1% of males and 5% of females still have problems.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Rates appear to be lower in rural societies.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] While some research has found it affects people of all ethnic groups, acne may not occur in the non-Westernized peoples of Papua New Guinea and Paraguay.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne affects 40–50 million people in the United States (16%) and approximately 3–5 million in Australia (23%).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Severe acne tends to be more common in people of Caucasian or Amerindian descent than in people of African descent.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Historical records indicate that pharaohs had acne, which may be the earliest known reference to the disease.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Sulfur's usefulness as a topical remedy for acne dates back to at least the reign of Cleopatra (69–30 BCE).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The sixth-century Greek physician Aëtius of Amida reportedly coined the term "*ionthos*" (ίονθωξ,) or "*acnae*", which seems to be a reference to facial skin lesions that occur during "the 'acme' of life" (puberty).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In the 16th century, the French physician and botanist François Boissier de Sauvages de Lacroix provided one of the earlier descriptions of acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] He used the term "psydracia achne" to describe small, red, and hard tubercles that altered a person's facial appearance during adolescence and were neither itchy nor painful.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The recognition and characterization of acne progressed in 1776 when Josef Plenck (an Austrian physician) published a book that proposed the novel concept of classifying skin diseases by their elementary (initial) lesions.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In 1808 the English dermatologist Robert Willan refined Plenck's work by providing the first detailed descriptions of several skin disorders using morphologic terminology that remains in use today.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Thomas Bateman continued and expanded on Robert Willan's work as his student and provided the first descriptions and illustrations of acne accepted as accurate by modern dermatologists.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Erasmus Wilson, in 1842, was the first to make the distinction between acne vulgaris and rosacea.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The first professional medical monograph dedicated entirely to acne was written by Lucius Duncan Bulkley and published in New York in 1885.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Scientists initially hypothesized that acne represented a disease of the skin's hair follicle, and occurred due to blockage of the pore by sebum.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] During the 1880s, they observed bacteria by microscopy in skin samples from people with acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Investigators believed the bacteria caused comedones, sebum production, and ultimately acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] During the mid-twentieth century, dermatologists realized that no single hypothesized factor (sebum, bacteria, or excess keratin) fully accounted for the disease in its entirety.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] This led to the current understanding that acne could be explained by a sequence of related events, beginning with blockage of the skin follicle by excessive dead skin cells, followed by bacterial invasion of the hair follicle pore, changes in sebum production, and inflammation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The approach to acne treatment underwent significant changes during the twentieth century.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Retinoids became a medical treatment for acne in 1943.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Benzoyl peroxide was first proposed as a treatment in 1958 and remains a staple of acne treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The introduction of oral tetracycline antibiotics (such as minocycline) modified acne treatment in the 1950s.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] These reinforced the idea amongst dermatologists that bacterial growth on the skin plays an important role in causing acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Subsequently, in the 1970s, tretinoin (original trade name Retin A) was found to be an effective treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The development of oral isotretinoin (sold as Accutane and Roaccutane) followed.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] After its introduction in the United States in 1982, scientists identified isotretinoin as a medication highly likely to cause birth defects if taken during pregnancy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In the United States, more than 2,000 women became pregnant while taking isotretinoin between 1982 and 2003, with most pregnancies ending in abortion or miscarriage.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Approximately 160 babies were born with birth defects due to maternal use of isotretinoin during pregnancy.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Treatment of acne with topical crushed dry ice, known as cryoslush, was first described in 1907 but is no longer performed commonly.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Before 1960, the use of X-rays was also a common treatment.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The costs and social impact of acne are substantial.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In the United States, acne vulgaris is responsible for more than 5 million doctor visits and costs over US$2.5 billion each year in direct costs.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Similarly, acne vulgaris is responsible for 3.5 million doctor visits each year in the United Kingdom.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Sales for the top ten leading acne treatment brands in the US in 2015 amounted to $352 million.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne vulgaris and its resultant scars are associated with significant social and academic difficulties that can last into adulthood.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] During the Great Depression, dermatologists discovered that young men with acne had difficulty obtaining jobs.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Until the 1930s, many people viewed acne as a trivial problem among middle-class girls because, unlike smallpox and tuberculosis, no one died from it, and a feminine problem, because boys were much less likely to seek medical assistance for it.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] During World War II, some American soldiers in tropical climates developed such severe and widespread tropical acne on their bodies that they were declared medically unfit for duty.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Efforts to better understand the mechanisms of sebum production are underway.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] This research aims to develop medications that target and interfere with the hormones that are known to increase sebum production (e.g., IGF-1 and alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Other sebum-lowering medications such as topical antiandrogens, peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor modulators, and inhibitors of the stearoyl-CoA desaturase-1 enzyme are also a focus of research efforts.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Particles that release nitric oxide into the skin to decrease skin inflammation caused by *C. acnes* and the immune system have shown promise for improving acne in early clinical trials.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Another avenue of early-stage research has focused on how to best use laser and light therapy to selectively destroy sebum-producing glands in the skin's hair follicles to reduce sebum production and improve acne appearance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The use of antimicrobial peptides against *C. acnes* is under investigation as a treatment for acne to overcoming antibiotic resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] In 2007, scientists reported the first genome sequencing of a *C. acnes* bacteriophage (PA6).
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] The authors proposed applying this research toward the development of bacteriophage therapy as an acne treatment to overcome the problems associated with long-term antibiotic use, such as bacterial resistance.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Oral and topical probiotics are under evaluation as treatments for acne.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Probiotics may have therapeutic effects for those affected by acne due to their ability to decrease skin inflammation and improve skin moisture by increasing the skin's ceramide content.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] As of 2014, knowledge of the effects of probiotics on acne in humans was limited.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Decreased levels of retinoic acid in the skin may contribute to comedo formation.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Researchers are investigating methods to increase the skin's production of retinoic acid to address this deficiency.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] A vaccine against inflammatory acne has shown promising results in mice and humans.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Some have voiced concerns about creating a vaccine designed to neutralize a stable community of normal skin bacteria that is known to protect the skin from colonization by more harmful microorganisms.
[src:gas-mask/acne-p02] Acne can occur on cats, dogs, and horses.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Because it is so porous on a microscopic scale, activated carbon has a surface area of over 3,000 square metres per gram (920,000 square feet per ounce), as determined by gas absorption, and its porosity can run 10ML/day in terms of treated water per gram.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Researchers at Cornell University synthesized an ultrahigh surface area activated carbon with a BET area of 4,800 m2/g (1,500,000 sq ft/oz).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This BET area value is the highest reported in the literature for activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] For charcoal, the equivalent figure before activation is about 2–5 square metres per gram (610–1,530 sq ft/oz).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A useful activation level may be obtained solely from the high surface area.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Further chemical treatment often enhances adsorption properties.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is usually derived from waste products such as coconut husks in addition to other agricultural wastes like olive stones, rice husks and nutshells which are being upcycled into activated carbon, diversifying feedstock supply.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Waste from paper mills has been studied as a possible source of activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] These bulk sources are converted into charcoal before being activated.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Using waste streams not only reduces landfill burden but also works to lower the overall carbon footprint as previously discarded waste is repurposed.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] When derived from coal, it is referred to as **activated coal**.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] **Activated coke** is derived from coke.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] These multiuse applications make it a versatile form of carbon that is used daily in many industries.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] There are many industrial applications of activated carbon and its other forms such as areas like metal extraction, water purification, sewage treatment, metal finishing and more.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] For example, it is the main purification technique for removing organic impurities from bright nickel plating solutions used for metal finishing plants.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Expanding on electroplating, a variety of organic chemicals can be added to the plating solutions for improving their deposit qualities and for enhancing properties like brightness, smoothness, ductility, etc.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This is due to the passage of direct current and electrolytic reactions of anodic oxidation and cathodic reduction, organic additives generate unwanted breakdown products in solution.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Their excessive build up in the solutions can adversely affect plating quality and physical properties of deposited metal if run untreated by the filters.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon treatment removes such impurities and restores plating performance to the desired level.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Its installation costs may vary according to the volume of water it must process, however the average cost can be around USD 1 - 2 million.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Additionally, these filters need replacing over time (typically 6–12 months depending on usage).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The cost of replacing the carbon in the GAC filter form is about USD 0.05 - 0.1 per cubic meter of water that is treated in the plant.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is used to treat poisonings and overdoses following oral ingestion.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Tablets or capsules of activated carbon are used in many countries as an over-the-counter drug to treat diarrhea, indigestion, and flatulence.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon will not prevent these chemicals from being absorbed into the human body.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Incorrect application (e.g. into the lungs) results in pulmonary aspiration, which can sometimes be fatal if immediate medical treatment is not initiated.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon, in 50% w/w combination with celite, is used as stationary phase in low-pressure chromatographic separation of carbohydrates (mono-, di-, tri-saccharides) using ethanol solutions (5–50%) as mobile phase in analytical or preparative protocols.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is useful for extracting the direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) such as dabigatran, apixaban, rivaroxaban and edoxaban from blood plasma samples.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] For this purpose it has been made into "minitablets", each containing 5 mg activated carbon for treating 1ml samples of DOAC.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Since this activated carbon has no effect on blood clotting factors, heparin or most other anticoagulants this allows a plasma sample to be analyzed for abnormalities otherwise affected by the DOACs.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] During early implementation of the 1974 Safe Drinking Water Act in the US, EPA officials developed a rule that proposed requiring drinking water treatment systems to use granular activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Because of its high cost, the so-called GAC rule encountered strong opposition across the country from the water supply industry, including the largest water utilities in California.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filtration is an effective water treatment method due to its multi-functional nature.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] There are specific types of activated carbon filtration methods and equipment that are indicated – depending upon the contaminants involved.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In wastewater treatment, granulated activated carbon filters are implemented as an additional treatment step for removal of organic micropollutants such as pharmaceutical products, many of which are not entirely removed in traditional wastewater treatment processes.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Pollutants adsorb to the activated carbon granules and are then degraded by microorganisms on the filters.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is also used for the measurement of radon concentration in air.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Biomass waste-derived activated carbons were also successfully used for the removal of caffeine and paracetamol from water.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon (charcoal) is an allowed substance used by organic farmers in both livestock production and wine making.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In livestock production it is used as a pesticide, animal feed additive, processing aid, nonagricultural ingredient and disinfectant.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In organic winemaking, activated carbon is allowed for use as a processing agent to adsorb brown color pigments from white grape concentrates.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filters (AC filters) can be used to filter vodka and whiskey of organic impurities which can affect color, taste, and odor.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Passing an organically impure vodka through an activated carbon filter at the proper flow rate will result in vodka with an identical alcohol content and significantly increased organic purity, as judged by odor and taste.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Research is being done testing various activated carbons' ability to store natural gas and hydrogen gas.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The porous material acts like a sponge for different types of gases.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The gas is attracted to the carbon material via Van der Waals forces.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Some carbons have been able to achieve binding energies of 5–10 kJ per mol.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The gas may then be desorbed when subjected to higher temperatures and either combusted to do work or in the case of hydrogen gas extracted for use in a hydrogen fuel cell.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Gas storage in activated carbons is an appealing gas storage method because the gas can be stored in a low pressure, low mass, low volume environment that would be much more feasible than bulky on-board pressure tanks in vehicles.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The United States Department of Energy has specified certain goals to be achieved in the area of research and development of nano-porous carbon materials.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] All of the goals are yet to be satisfied but numerous institutions, including the ALL-CRAFT program, are continuing to conduct work in this field.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Filters with activated carbon are usually used in compressed air and gas purification to remove oil vapors, odor, and other hydrocarbons from the air.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The most common designs use a 1-stage or 2 stage filtration principle in which activated carbon is embedded inside the filter media.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon filters are used to retain radioactive gases within the air vacuumed from a nuclear boiling water reactor turbine condenser.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The large charcoal beds adsorb these gases and retain them while they rapidly decay to nonradioactive solid species.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The solids are trapped in the charcoal particles, while the filtered air passes through.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is commonly used on the laboratory scale to purify solutions of organic molecules containing unwanted colored organic impurities.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Filtration over activated carbon is used in large scale fine chemical and pharmaceutical processes for the same purpose.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The carbon is either mixed with the solution then filtered off or immobilized in a filter.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon, often infused with sulfur or iodine, is widely used to trap mercury emissions from coal-fired power stations, medical incinerators, and from natural gas at the wellhead.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, despite its effectiveness, activated carbon is expensive to use.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Since it is often not recycled, the mercury-laden activated carbon presents a disposal dilemma.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] If the activated carbon contains less than 260 ppm mercury, United States federal regulations allow it to be stabilized (for example, trapped in concrete) for landfilling.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, waste containing greater than 260 ppm is considered to be in the high-mercury subcategory and is banned from landfilling (Land-Ban Rule).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This material is now accumulating in warehouses and in deep abandoned mines at an estimated rate of 100 tons per year.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The problem of disposal of mercury-laden activated carbon is not unique to the United States.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In the Netherlands, this mercury is largely recovered and the activated carbon is disposed of by complete burning, forming carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated, food-grade charcoal became a food trend in 2016, being used as an additive to impart a "slightly smoky" taste and a dark coloring to products including hotdogs, ice cream, pizza bases, and bagels.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] People taking medication, including birth control pills and antidepressants, are advised to avoid novelty foods or drinks that use activated charcoal coloring since it can render the medication ineffective.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated charcoal is used in smoking filters as a way to reduce the tar content and other chemicals present in smoke, which is a result of combustion, wherein it has been found to reduce the toxicants from tobacco smoke, in particular the free radicals.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The structure of activated carbon has long been a subject of debate.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In a book published in 2006, Harry Marsh and Francisco Rodríguez-Reinoso considered more than 15 models for the structure, without coming to a definite conclusion about which was correct.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Recent work using aberration-corrected transmission electron microscopy has suggested that activated carbons may have a structure related to that of the fullerenes, with pentagonal and heptagonal carbon rings.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon is carbon produced from carbonaceous source materials such as bamboo, coconut husk, willow peat, wood, coir, lignite, coal, and petroleum pitch.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The source material is carbonized through pyrolysis at temperatures in the range 600–900 °C, usually in an inert atmosphere with gases such as argon or nitrogen.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] **Chemical activation**: Carbonaceous material is impregnated with certain chemicals.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The chemical is typically an acid, strong base, or a salt (phosphoric acid, potassium hydroxide, sodium hydroxide, potassium carbonate, sodium chloride, sodium carbonate, calcium chloride, and zinc chloride).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The carbon is then subjected to high temperatures (250–800 °C).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is believed that the temperature activates the carbon at this stage by forcing the material to open up and have more microscopic pores.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Chemical activation is preferred to physical activation owing to the lower temperatures, better quality consistency, and shorter time needed for activating the material.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The Dutch company Norit NV is one of the largest producer of activated carbon in the world.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Haycarb, a Sri Lankan coconut shell-based company, controls 16% of the global market share.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] After adsorption, spent granular activated carbon can often be regenerated rather than discarded.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Thermal reactivation (heating in an inert or steam atmosphere at 800–900 °C) restores much of the pore structure but consumes significant energy, while chemical regeneration (e.g. with dilute acids or bases) can selectively remove fouling compounds under milder conditions.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Emerging methods like microwave-assisted reactivation and bio-regeneration using fungi or bacteria show promise for lower-carbon footprints.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Choosing the optimal regeneration route balances carbon lifespan, energy use and treatment costs, and helps minimize the volume of hazardous waste sent to landfill.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbons are complex products which are difficult to classify on the basis of their behaviour, surface characteristics and other fundamental criteria.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, some broad classification is made for general purposes based on their size, preparation methods, and industrial applications.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Normally, activated carbons (R 1) are made in particulate form as powders or fine granules less than 1.0 mm in size with an average diameter between 0.15 and 0.25 mm.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Thus they present a large surface to volume ratio with a small diffusion distance.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon (R 1) is defined as the activated carbon particles retained on a 50-mesh sieve (0.297 mm).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Powdered activated carbon (PAC) material is finer material.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] PAC is made up of crushed or ground carbon particles, 95–100% of which will pass through a designated mesh sieve.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The ASTM classifies particles passing through an 80-mesh sieve (0.177 mm) and smaller as PAC.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is not common to use PAC in a dedicated vessel, due to the high head loss that would occur.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Instead, PAC is generally added directly to other process units, such as raw water intakes, rapid mix basins, clarifiers, and gravity filters.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Granular activated carbon (GAC) has a relatively larger particle size compared to powdered activated carbon and consequently, presents a smaller external surface.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Diffusion of the adsorbate is thus an important factor.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] These carbons are suitable for adsorption of gases, vapors and liquids, because these substances diffuse rapidly throughout the filters.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Granulated carbons are used for air filtration and water treatment, as well as for general deodorization and separation of components in flow systems and in rapid mix basins.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] GAC can be obtained in either granular or extruded form.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] GAC is designated by sizes such as 8×20, 20×40, or 8×30 for liquid phase applications and 4×6, 4×8 or 4×10 for vapor phase applications.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A 20×40 carbon is made of particles that will pass through a U.S.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] 20 sieve (0.84 mm) (generally specified as 85% passing) but be retained on a U.S.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] 40 sieve (0.42 mm) (generally specified as 95% retained).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] AWWA (1992) B604 uses the 50-mesh sieve (0.297 mm) as the minimum GAC size.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The most popular aqueous-phase carbons are the 12×40 and 8×30 sizes because they have a good balance of size, surface area, and head loss characteristics.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Extruded activated carbon (EAC) combines powdered activated carbon with a binder, which are fused together and extruded into a cylindrical shaped activated carbon block with diameters from 0.8 to 130 mm.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] These are mainly used for gas phase applications because of their low pressure drop, high mechanical strength and low dust content.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Also sold as CTO filter (Chlorine, Taste, Odor).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Bead activated carbon (BAC) is manufactured from carbonizing petroleum pitch and then activating it into uniform spheres in diameters from approximately 0.35 to 0.80 mm.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] BAC typically exhibits a surface area in the range of 800–1 200 m2/g, comparable to or exceeding many granular carbons, enhancing its capacity for dissolved organics.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Similar to EAC, it is also noted for its low pressure drop, high mechanical strength and low dust content, but with a smaller grain size.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Its spherical shape makes it preferred for fluidized bed applications such as water filtration.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Porous carbons containing several types of inorganic impregnate such as iodine and silver.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Cations such as aluminium, manganese, zinc, iron, lithium, and calcium have also been prepared for specific application in air pollution control especially in museums and galleries.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Due to its antimicrobial and antiseptic properties, silver loaded activated carbon is used as an adsorbent for purification of domestic water.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Drinking water can be obtained from natural water by treating the natural water with a mixture of activated carbon and aluminium hydroxide (Al(OH)3), a flocculating agent.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Impregnated carbons are also used for the adsorption of hydrogen sulfide (H2S) and thiols.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Adsorption rates for H2S as high as 50% by weight have been reported.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This is a process by which a porous carbon can be coated with a biocompatible polymer to give a smooth and permeable coat without blocking the pores.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The typical film thickness ranges from 50 to 200 nm, which strikes a balance between preserving pore access and ensuring mechanical stability in the material.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The resulting carbon is useful for hemoperfusion.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Hemoperfusion is a treatment technique in which large volumes of the patient's blood are passed over an adsorbent substance in order to remove toxic substances from the blood.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In clinical trials, polymer-coated carbons have achieved over 80% removal of toxins such as bilirubin and certain drug metabolites in a single pass.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] There is a technology of processing technical rayon fiber into activated carbon cloth for carbon filtering.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Adsorption capacity of activated cloth is greater than that of activated charcoal (BET theory) surface area: 500–1500 m2/g, pore volume: 0.3–0.8 cm3/g).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Thanks to the different forms of activated material, it can be used in a wide range of applications (supercapacitors, odor absorbers, CBRN-defense industry etc.).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A gram of activated carbon can have a surface area in excess of 500 m2 (5,400 sq ft), with 3,000 m2 (32,000 sq ft) being readily achievable.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Carbon aerogels, while more expensive, have even higher surface areas, and are used in special applications.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Under an electron microscope, the high surface-area structures of activated carbon are revealed.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Individual particles are intensely convoluted and display various kinds of porosity; there may be many areas where flat surfaces of graphite-like material run parallel to each other, separated by only a few nanometres or so.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] These micropores provide superb conditions for adsorption to occur, since adsorbing material can interact with many surfaces simultaneously.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] James Dewar, the scientist after whom the Dewar (vacuum flask) is named, spent much time in the early 20th century studying activated carbon, and published a paper regarding its adsorption capacity with regard to gases.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In this paper, he discovered that cooling the carbon to liquid nitrogen temperatures allowed it to adsorb significant quantities of numerous air gases, among others, that could then be recollected by simply allowing the carbon to warm again and that coconut-based carbon was superior for the effect.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] He uses oxygen as an example, wherein the activated carbon would typically adsorb the atmospheric concentration (21%) under standard conditions, but release over 80% oxygen if the carbon was first cooled to low temperatures.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Physically, activated carbon binds materials by van der Waals force or London dispersion force.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon does not bind well to certain chemicals, including alcohols, diols, strong acids and bases, metals and most inorganics, such as lithium, sodium, iron, lead, arsenic, fluorine, and boric acid.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can also adsorb iodine very well.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The iodine capacity, mg/g, (ASTM D28 Standard Method test) may be used as an indication of total adsorption over the surface area of the testing material.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Carbon monoxide however, is not very well adsorbed by activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This should be of particular concern to those using the material in filters for respirators, fume hoods, or other gas control systems because the gas is undetectable to the human senses, toxic to the metabolism, and neurotoxic which creates concern.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Substantial lists of the common industrial and agricultural gases adsorbed by activated carbon can be found online.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can be used as a substrate for the application of various chemicals to improve the adsorptive capacity for some inorganic (and problematic organic) compounds such as hydrogen sulfide (H2S), ammonia (NH3), formaldehyde (HCOH), mercury (Hg) and radioactive iodine-131(131I).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This property is known as chemisorption.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Many carbons preferentially adsorb small molecules.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Iodine number is the most fundamental parameter used to characterize activated carbon performance.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is a measure of activity level (higher number indicates higher degree of activation) often reported in mg/g (typical range 500–1200 mg/g).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is a measure of the micropore content of the activated carbon (0 to 20 Å, or up to 2 nm) by adsorption of iodine from solution.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is equivalent to surface area of carbon between 900 and 1100 m2/g.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is the standard measure for liquid-phase applications.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Iodine number is defined as the milligrams of iodine adsorbed by one gram of carbon when the iodine concentration in the residual filtrate is at a concentration of 0.02 normal (i.e.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Basically, iodine number is a measure of the iodine adsorbed in the pores and, as such, is an indication of the pore volume available in the activated carbon of interest.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Typically, water-treatment carbons have iodine numbers ranging from 600 to 1100.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Frequently, this parameter is used to determine the degree of exhaustion of a carbon in use.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, this practice should be viewed with caution, as chemical interactions with the adsorbate may affect the iodine uptake, giving false results.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Some carbons are more adept at adsorbing large molecules.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Molasses number or molasses efficiency is a measure of the mesopore content of the activated carbon (greater than 20 Å, or larger than 2 nm) by adsorption of molasses from solution.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A high molasses number indicates a high adsorption of big molecules (range 95–600).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Caramel dp (decolorizing performance) is similar to molasses number.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Molasses efficiency is reported as a percentage (range 40%–185%) and parallels molasses number (600 = 185%, 425 = 85%).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The European molasses number (range 525–110) is inversely related to the North American molasses number.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Molasses Number is a measure of the degree of decolorization of a standard molasses solution that has been diluted and standardized against standardized activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Due to the size of color bodies, the molasses number represents the potential pore volume available for larger adsorbing species.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] As all of the pore volume may not be available for adsorption in a particular waste water application, and as some of the adsorbate may enter smaller pores, it is not a good measure of the worth of a particular activated carbon for a specific application.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Frequently, this parameter is useful in evaluating a series of active carbons for their rates of adsorption.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Given two active carbons with similar pore volumes for adsorption, the one having the higher molasses number will usually have larger feeder pores resulting in more efficient transfer of adsorbate into the adsorption space.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Tannins are a mixture of large and medium size molecules.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Carbons with a combination of macropores and mesopores adsorb tannins.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The ability of a carbon to adsorb tannins is reported in parts per million concentration (range 200 ppm–362 ppm).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Some carbons have a mesopore (20 Å to 50 Å, or 2 to 5 nm) structure which adsorbs medium size molecules, such as the dye methylene blue.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Methylene blue adsorption is reported in g/100g (range 11–28 g/100g).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Some carbons are evaluated based on the dechlorination half-life length, which measures the chlorine-removal efficiency of activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The dechlorination half-value length is the depth of carbon required to reduce the chlorine concentration by 50%.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A lower half-value length indicates superior performance.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The solid or skeletal density of activated carbons will typically range between 2000 and 2100 kg/m3 (125–130 lbs./cubic foot).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, a large part of an activated carbon sample will consist of air space between particles, and the actual or apparent density will therefore be lower, typically 400 to 500 kg/m3 (25–31 lbs./cubic foot).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Higher density provides greater volume activity and normally indicates better-quality activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] ASTM D 2854 -09 (2014) is used to determine the apparent density of activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is a measure of the activated carbon's resistance to attrition.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is an important indicator of activated carbon to maintain its physical integrity and withstand frictional forces which would cause the material to be defective.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] There are large differences in the hardness of activated carbons, depending on the raw material and activity levels (porosity) it is created for.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Ash reduces the overall activity of activated carbon and reduces the efficiency of reactivation.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The amount is exclusively dependent on the base raw material used to produce the activated carbon (e.g., coconut, wood, coal, etc.).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The metal oxides (Fe2O3) can leach out of activated carbon resulting in discoloration.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Acid/water-soluble ash content is more significant than total ash content.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Soluble ash content can be very important for aquarists, as ferric oxide can promote algal growths.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] A carbon with a low soluble ash content should be used for marine, freshwater fish and reef tanks to avoid heavy metal poisoning and excess plant/algal growth.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] ASTM (D2866 Standard Method test) is used to determine the ash content of activated carbon.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Measurement of the porosity of an activated carbon by the adsorption of saturated carbon tetrachloride vapour.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The finer the particle size of an activated carbon, the better the access to the surface area and the faster the rate of adsorption kinetics.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] In vapour phase systems this needs to be considered against pressure drop, which will affect energy cost.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Careful consideration of particle size distribution can provide significant operating benefits.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] However, in the case of using activated carbon for adsorption of minerals such as gold, the particle size should be in the range of 3.35–1.4 millimetres (0.132–0.055 in).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon with particle size less than 1 mm would not be suitable for elution (the stripping of mineral from an activated carbon).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Researchers at Cornell University synthesized an ultrahigh surface area activated carbon with a BET area of 4800 m2 g–1 and a total pore volume of 2.7 cm3 g–1.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] This BET area value is the highest reported in the literature for activated carbon to date.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Acid-base, oxidation-reduction and specific adsorption characteristics are strongly dependent on the composition of the surface functional groups.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The surface of conventional activated carbon is reactive, capable of oxidation by atmospheric oxygen and oxygen plasma steam, and also carbon dioxide and ozone.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Oxidation in the liquid phase is caused by a wide range of reagents (HNO3, H2O2, KMnO4).
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Through the formation of a large number of basic and acidic groups on the surface of oxidized carbon to sorption and other properties can differ significantly from the unmodified forms.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can be nitrogenated by natural products or polymers or processing of carbon with nitrogenating reagents.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Activated carbon can interact with chlorine, bromine and fluorine.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Surface of activated carbon, like other carbon materials can be fluoralkylated by treatment with (per)fluoropolyether peroxide in a liquid phase, or with wide range of fluoroorganic substances by CVD-method.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Such materials combine high hydrophobicity and chemical stability with electrical and thermal conductivity and can be used as electrode material for super capacitors.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Sulfonic acid functional groups can be attached to activated carbon to give "starbons" which can be used to selectively catalyse the esterification of fatty acids.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Formation of such activated carbons from halogenated precursors gives a more effective catalyst which is thought to be a result of remaining halogens improving stability.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] It is reported about synthesis of activated carbon with chemically grafted superacid sites –CF2SO3H.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Some of the chemical properties of activated carbon have been attributed to presence of the surface active carbon double bond.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The Polyani adsorption theory is a popular method for analyzing adsorption of various organic substances to their surface.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The most commonly encountered form of chemisorption in industry, occurs when a solid catalyst interacts with a gaseous feedstock, the reactant/s.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The adsorption of reactant/s to the catalyst surface creates a chemical bond, altering the electron density around the reactant molecule and allowing it to undergo reactions that would not normally be available to it.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The reactivation or the regeneration of activated carbons involves restoring the adsorptive capacity of saturated activated carbon by desorbing adsorbed contaminants on the activated carbon surface.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The most common regeneration technique employed in industrial processes is thermal reactivation.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The heat treatment stage utilises the exothermic nature of adsorption and results in desorption, partial cracking and polymerization of the adsorbed organics.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] The final step aims to remove charred organic residue formed in the porous structure in the previous stage and re-expose the porous carbon structure regenerating its original surface characteristics.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] After treatment the adsorption column can be reused.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Per adsorption-thermal regeneration cycle between 5–15 wt% of the carbon bed is burnt off resulting in a loss of adsorptive capacity.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Thermal regeneration is a high energy process due to the high required temperatures making it both an energetically and commercially expensive process.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Plants that rely on thermal regeneration of activated carbon have to be of a certain size before it is economically viable to have regeneration facilities onsite.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] As a result, it is common for smaller waste treatment sites to ship their activated carbon cores to specialised facilities for regeneration.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Current concerns with the high energy/cost nature of thermal regeneration of activated carbon has encouraged research into alternative regeneration methods to reduce the environmental impact of such processes.
[src:gas-mask/activated-carbon] Though several of the regeneration techniques cited have remained areas of purely academic research, some alternatives to thermal regeneration systems have been employed in industry.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] A **gas mask** is a piece of personal protective equipment used to protect the wearer from inhaling airborne pollutants and toxic gases.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The mask forms a sealed cover over the nose and mouth, but may also cover the eyes and other vulnerable soft tissues of the face.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Most gas masks are also respirators, though the word *gas mask* is often used to refer to military equipment (such as a field protective mask), the scope used in this article.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Gas masks only protect the user from ingesting or inhaling chemical agents, as well as preventing contact with the user's eyes (many chemical agents affect through eye contact).
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Most combined gas mask filters will last around 8 hours in a biological or chemical situation.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Filters against specific chemical agents can last up to 20 hours.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Airborne toxic materials may be gaseous (for example, chlorine or mustard gas), or particulates (such as biological agents).
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Many filters provide protection from both types.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Modern gas masks developed during World War I featured circular lenses made of glass, mica or cellulose acetate to allow vision.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Glass and mica were quite brittle and needed frequent replacement.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The later Triplex lens style (a cellulose acetate lens sandwiched between glass ones) became more popular, and alongside plain cellulose acetate they became the standard into the 1930s.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Panoramic lenses were not popular until the 1930s.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Later, stronger polycarbonate came into use.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Some masks have one or two compact air filter containers screwed onto inlets, while others have a large air filtration container connected to the gas mask via a hose that is sometimes confused with an *air-supplied respirator* in which an alternate supply of fresh air (oxygen tanks) is delivered.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] According to *Popular Mechanics*, "The common sponge was used in ancient Greece as a gas mask..." In 1785, Jean-François Pilâtre de Rozier invented a respirator.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Primitive respirator examples were used by miners and introduced by Alexander von Humboldt in 1799, when he worked as a mining engineer in Prussia.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The forerunner to the modern gas mask was invented in 1847 by Lewis P.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Haslett, a device that contained elements that allowed breathing through a nose and mouthpiece, inhalation of air through a bulb-shaped filter, and a vent to exhale air back into the atmosphere.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] *First Facts* states that a "gas mask resembling the modern type" was patented by Lewis Phectic Haslett of Louisville, Kentucky, who received a patent on June 12, 1849.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] U.S. patent #6,529 issued to Haslett, described the first "Inhaler or Lung Protector" that filtered dust from the air.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Early versions were constructed by the Scottish chemist John Stenhouse in 1854 and the physicist John Tyndall in the 1870s.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Another early design was the "Safety Hood and Smoke Protector" invented by Garrett Morgan in 1912, and patented in 1914.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] It was a simple device consisting of a cotton hood with two hoses which hung down to the floor, allowing the wearer to breathe the safer air found there.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In addition, moist sponges were inserted at the end of the hoses in order to better filter the air.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The First World War brought about the first need for mass-produced gas masks on both sides because of extensive use of chemical weapons.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The German army successfully used poison gas for the first time against Allied troops at the Second Battle of Ypres, Belgium on April 22, 1915.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] An immediate response was cotton wool wrapped in muslin, issued to the troops by May 1.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This was followed by the Black Veil Respirator, invented by John Scott Haldane, which was a cotton pad soaked in an absorbent solution which was secured over the mouth using black cotton veiling.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Seeking to improve on the Black Veil respirator, Cluny Macpherson created a mask made of chemical-absorbing fabric which fitted over the entire head: a 50.5 cm × 48 cm (19.9 in × 18.9 in) canvas hood treated with chlorine-absorbing chemicals, and fitted with a transparent mica eyepiece.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Macpherson presented his idea to the British War Office Anti-Gas Department on May 10, 1915; prototypes were developed soon after.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The design was adopted by the British Army and introduced as the British Smoke Hood in June 1915; Macpherson was appointed to the War Office Committee for Protection against Poisonous Gases.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] More elaborate sorbent compounds were added later to further iterations of his helmet (PH helmet), to defeat other respiratory poison gases used such as phosgene, diphosgene and chloropicrin.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In summer and autumn 1915, Edward Harrison, Bertram Lambert and John Sadd developed the Large Box Respirator.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This canister gas mask had a tin can containing the absorbent materials by a hose and began to be issued in February 1916.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] A compact version, the Small Box Respirator, was made a universal issue from August 1916.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In the first gas masks of World War I, it was initially found that wood charcoal was a good absorbent of poison gases.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Around 1918, it was found that charcoals made from the shells and seeds of various fruits and nuts such as coconuts, chestnuts, horse-chestnuts, and peach stones performed much better than wood charcoal.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] These waste materials were collected from the public in recycling programs to assist the war effort.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The first effective filtering activated charcoal gas mask in the world was invented in 1915 by Russian chemist Nikolay Zelinsky.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Also in World War I, since dogs were frequently used on the front lines, a special type of gas mask was developed that dogs were trained to wear.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Other gas masks were developed during World War I and the time following for horses in the various mounted units that operated near the front lines.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In America, thousands of gas masks were produced for American as well as Allied troops.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Mine Safety Appliances was a chief producer.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This mask was later used widely in industry.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The British Respirator, Anti-Gas (Light) was developed in 1943 by the British.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] It was made of plastic and rubber-like material that greatly reduced the weight and bulk compared to World War I gas masks, and fitted the user's face more snugly and comfortably.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The main improvement was replacing the separate filter canister connected with a hose by an easily replaceable filter canister screwed on the side of the gas mask.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Also, it had replaceable plastic lenses.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Gas mask development since has mirrored the development of chemical agents in warfare, filling the need to protect against ever more deadly threats, biological weapons, and radioactive dust in the nuclear era.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] However, for agents that cause harm through contact or penetration of the skin, such as blister agent or nerve agent, a gas mask alone is not sufficient protection, and full protective clothing must be worn in addition to protect from contact with the atmosphere.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Most military gas masks are designed to be capable of protecting against all NBC agents, but they can have filter canisters proof against those agents (heavier) or only against riot control agents and smoke (lighter and often used for training purposes).
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] There are lightweight masks solely for protection against riot-control agents and not for NBC situations.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] During the Iran–Iraq War (1980–88), Iraq developed its chemical weapons program with the help of European countries such as Germany and France and used them in a large scale against Iranians and Iraqi Kurds.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Iran was unprepared for chemical warfare.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In 1984, Iran received gas masks from the Republic of Korea and East Germany, but the Korean masks were not suited for the faces of non-East Asian people, the filter lasted for only 15 minutes, and the 5,000 masks bought from East Germany proved to be not gas masks but spray-painting goggles.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] As late as 1986, Iranian diplomats still travelled in Europe to buy active charcoal and models of filters to produce defensive gear domestically.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In April 1988, Iran started domestic production of gas masks by the Iran Yasa factories.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Absorption is the process of being drawn into a (usually larger) body or substrate, and adsorption is the process of deposition upon a surface.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This can be used to remove both particulate and gaseous hazards.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Although some form of reaction may take place, it is not necessary; the method may work by attractive charges.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] For example, if the target particles are positively charged, a negatively charged substrate may be used.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Examples of substrates include activated carbon, and zeolites.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This effect can be very simple and highly effective, for example using a damp cloth to cover the mouth and nose while escaping a fire.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] While this method can be effective at trapping particulates produced by combustion, it does not filter out harmful gases which may be toxic or which displace the oxygen required for survival.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Gas masks have a useful lifespan limited by the absorbent capacity of the filter.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Filters cease to provide protection when saturated with hazardous chemicals, and degrade over time even if sealed.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Most gas masks have sealing caps over the air intake and are stored in vacuum-sealed bags to prevent the filter from degrading due to exposure to humidity and pollutants in normal air.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Unused gas mask filters from World War II may not protect the wearer at all, and could be harmful if worn due to long-term changes in the chemical composition of the filter.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Some World War II and Soviet Cold War gas mask filters contained chrysotile asbestos or crocidolite asbestos. not known to be harmful at the time.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] It is not reliably known for how long the materials were used in filters.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Typically, masks using 40 mm connections are a more recent design.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Rubber degrades with time, so boxed unused "modern type" masks can be cracked and leak.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The US C2 canister (black) contains hexavalent chromium; studies by the U.S.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Army Chemical Corps found that the level in the filter was acceptable, but suggest caution when using, as it is a carcinogen.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The filter is selected according to the toxic compound.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Particle filters are often included, because in many cases the hazardous materials are in the form of mist, which can be captured by the particle filter before entering the chemical adsorber.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In Europe and jurisdictions with similar rules such as Russia and Australia, filter types are given suffix numbers to indicate their capacity.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] For non-particle hazards, the level "1" is assumed and a number "2" is used to indicate a better level.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] For particles (P), three levels are always given with the number.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In the US, only the particle part is further classified by NIOSH air filtration ratings.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] A filter type that can protect against multiple hazards is notated with the European symbols concatenated with each other.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Examples include ABEK, ABEK-P3, and ABEK-HgP3.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] A2B2E2K2-P3 is the highest rating of filter available.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] An entirely different "multi/CBRN" filter class with an olive color is used in the US.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Filtration may be aided with an air pump to improve wearer comfort.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Filtration of air is only possible if there is sufficient oxygen in the first place.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Thus, when handling asphyxiants, or when ventilation is poor or the hazards are unknown, filtration is not possible and air must be supplied (with a SCBA system) from a pressurized bottle as in scuba diving.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] A modern mask typically is constructed of an elastic polymer in various sizes.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] It is fitted with various adjustable straps which may be tightened to secure a good fit.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Crucially, it is connected to a filter cartridge near the mouth either directly, or via a flexible hose.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Some models contain drinking tubes which may be connected to a water bottle.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Corrective lens inserts are also available for users who require them.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Masks are typically tested for fit before use.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] After a mask is fitted, it is often tested by various challenge agents.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Isoamyl acetate, a synthetic banana flavourant, and camphor are often used as innocuous challenge agents.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] In the military, teargases such as CN, CS, and stannic chloride in a chamber may be used to give the users confidence in the efficacy of the mask.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The protection of a gas mask comes with some disadvantages.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The wearer of a typical gas mask must exert extra effort to breathe, and some of the exhaled air is re-inhaled due to the dead space between the facepiece and the user's face.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] The UK HSE textbook recommends limiting the use of respirators without air supply (that is, not PAPR) to one hour.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This principle relies on substances harmful to humans being usually more reactive than air.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] This method of separation will use some form of generally reactive substance (for example an acid) coating or supported by some solid material.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] These can be created with different groups of atoms (usually called functional groups) that have different properties.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Thus a resin can be tailored to a particular toxic group.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] When the reactive substance comes in contact with the resin, it will bond to it, removing it from the air stream.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] It may also exchange with a less harmful substance at this site.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] Though it was crude, the hypo helmet was a stopgap measure for British troops in the trenches that offered at least some protection during a gas attack.
[src:gas-mask/gas-mask] As the months passed and poison gas was used more often, more sophisticated gas masks were developed and introduced.
